 address the complex set of questions that relate to economic wealth and its implications for social and political life in modern societies. The volume thus brings together a range of perspectives on wealth, inequality, capitalism, oligarchy, and democracy. The essays also cover a number of more specific topics including limitarianism, US Constitutional history, the wealth defense industry, slavery, and tax policy. Wealth offers analysis and prescription including original assessment of existing forms of economic wealth and creative policy responses for the negative implications of wealth inequality. Economic wealth and its distribution is a pressing issue and this latest installment in the NOMOS series offers new and thought provoking insights.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jun 2020) 0aDemocracyxEconomic aspectszUnited States. 0aDistributive justicezUnited States. 0aLaw and economics. 0aWealth - Political aspects - United States. 0aWealthzUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Economic Policy.2bisacsh1 aKnight, Jack, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSchwartzberg, Melissa, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479849291423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781479849291.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK